Condition : 5 - No development shall take place until a programme of phasing for the implementation of the whole development site, which takes into account the timescales set out in Conditions 1 and 2, has been submitted to and agreed in writing by the local planning authority. Development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved phasing programme.
The programme shall include details, where available, of the timing for delivery of:
? Hard/soft landscaping;
? The public open spaces;
? Other public realm relative to each phase

Reason: To ensure that the proposed development is carried out in accordance with the planning permission and scheme of works, and to avoid any detriment to the comprehensive development and to amenity and any harm to the interests of highway safety that may be caused by any phase remaining uncompleted in accordance with London Plan (2015) policy EC2, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework 2021.

Condition : 9 - Except for any works relating to demolition, site clearance, remediation, development shall not commence within a phase (or part therein), until details of the following have been submitted to and approved in writing by the LPA:
a) Housing Mix and Affordable Housing Statement;
b) BREEAM preliminary-assessment;
c) Car Parking Details;
d) Design Statement;
e) District Heating Network Assessment;
f) Energy Strategy;
g) Fire Strategy;
h) Landscaping Management Plan;
i) Lighting Strategy;
j) Inclusive Access Strategy;
k) Planning Statement;
l) Statement of Community Involvement;
m) Transport Assessment;
n) Whole Life Carbon Assessment;
o) Circular Economy Statement;
p) Floor, elevation and section plans;
q) Details of the internal space standards, house-size mix for the residential homes
r) A minimum of 10% of the total dwellings shall be constructed as 'Wheelchair User Dwellings' built to Building Regulations M4(3)2b standard shall be provided. All other dwellings shall be designed so that they meet building regulation M4(2) 'accessible and adaptable dwellings' requirements;
s) Daylight and Sunlight Report including shadow plot diagrams;
t) Details of play space, amenity space and landscaping strategy;
u) Details of the works to the public realm and highways, including any traffic calming measures;
v) Updated drainage assessment form, and assessment to demonstrate compliance with principles set out in the Flood Risk Assessment Report and Drainage Assessment (Produced by GDP, Dated: 17/01/2023; Ref: 21095-01 Rev C) and Drainage Assessment Form and associated drawings;
w) Ecology; enhancement and mitigation measures, urban greening factor and Biodiversity Net Gain Calculations.

Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interest of proper planning and to comply with the EIA Directive and to ensure that high standards of urban design, landscaping and environmental mitigation are achieved and that a proper record is kept, and in order that the C

Condition : 14 - Prior to the commencement of each phase of the development, including any demolition works, site preparation, ground works or vegetation clearance, a detailed Construction Environment Management Plan (CEMP) shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The CEMP shall provide details of how site preparation, vegetation clearance, demolition and construction works are to be undertaken and include:
i. The identification of stages of works;
ii. Risk assessment of potentially damaging construction activities to retained trees and ecology;
iii. Identify activities requiring licensing (such as ecology) and describe how these will be coordinated within the development programme of works;
iv. Identification of "biodiversity protection zones";
v. Procedures to prevent destruction of active birds nests;
vi. Provisions to practical measures and systems prevent environmental harm to priority habits, designated sites and water courses;
vii. The protection of trees during demolition and construction;
viii. The approach to be taken when dealing with habitat trees such those with bat roost suitability e.g. update inspections and further surveys;
ix. Measures to prevent harm to nocturnal mammals;
x. Practical measures (both physical measures and sensitive working practices) to avoid or reduce biodiversity impacts during construction (may be provided as a set of method statements);
xi. The location and timing of sensitive works to avoid harm to biodiversity features;
xii. The times during construction when specialist ecologists need to be present on site to oversee works;
xiii. Responsible persons and lines of communication;
xiv. The role and responsibilities on site of an ecological clerk of works (ECoW) or similarly competent person;
xv. Measures to mitigate noise, dust and air quality;
xvi. Setting of appropriate noise and vibration criteria at the worst-affected sensitive receptors;
xvii. Use of protective fences, exclusion barrier

Condition : 15 - Prior to the commencement of each phase of the development, including any demolition works and site preparation, a Construction Logistics Plan (CLP) shall be submitted to, and approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority. The Plan shall accord with TfL guidance and shall include:
i. a site plan (showing the areas set out below);
ii. confirmation that a pre-start record of site conditions on the adjoining public highway will be undertaken with Hounslow Highways and a commitment to repair any damage caused;
iii. a Staff Travel Plan to ensure that staff and contractors travel to the site by sustainable means;
iv. provision for the parking of vehicles of site operatives and visitors;
v. provisions for loading, unloading and storage of plant and materials within the site;
vi. details of access to the site, including means to control and manage access and egress of vehicles to and from the site for the duration of construction including phasing arrangements;
vii. details of working hours, which unless otherwise agreed with the Local Planning Authority shall be limited to 08:00 to 18:00 Monday to Friday and 08:00 to 13:00 on Saturdays);
viii. details of vehicle routeing from the site to the wider strategic road network;
ix. the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate;
x. provision of wheel washing facilities at the site exit and a commitment to sweep adjacent roads when required and at the request of the council;
xi. a scheme for recycling/disposing of waste resulting from demolition and construction works;
xii. measures to ensure the safety of all users of the public highway especially cyclists and pedestrians in the vicinity of the site and especially at the access;
xiii. commitment to liaise with other contractors in the vicinity of the site to maximise the potential for consolidation and to minimise traffic impacts;
xiv. avoidance of peak hours for deliveries

Condition : 23 - A. Prior to the commencement of above ground works on each phase (or part therein) of the development (except for any work relating to demolition, site clearance, remediation), a revised Energy Strategy must be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The revised Energy Strategy shall include: 
i. details of how the applicant has considered and minimised the estimated energy costs to occupants and outline how they are committed to protecting the consumer from high prices that includes a confirmation of the quality assurance mechanisms that will be considered as part of the strategy; 
ii. an Overheating Assessment for domestic and non-domestic spaces that includes a Dynamic Overheating Analysis. This should follow the CIBSE TM59 and Part O methodology for the London Design Summer Year 1 (DSY1) weather file: 2020s, High emission, 50% percentile scenario. The applicant should also investigate the risk of overheating using the DSY 2 & 3 weather files; 
iii. Climate Change Adaptation Strategy Appraisal to investigate the potential risk of a building fabric, structure and fa�ade design associated with climate change; 
iv. An estimate of the heating and/or cooling energy (MWh/annum) the heat pumps would provide to the development and the percentage of contribution to the site's heat loads. This shall demonstrate how the heat fraction from heat pump technologies has been maximised.
v. Details of the Seasonal Coefficient of Performance (SCOP) and/or Seasonal Energy Efficiency ratio (SEER) and how these have been calculated. This should incorporate the expected heat source and heat distribution temperatures (for space heat and hot water) and the distribution loss factor, which should be calculated based on the above information and used for calculation purposes.

